;;; this is where the IR will live. It should absorb the ISA of
;;; a CPU and: translate states; define defective states;
;;; define errors and their danger levels;
;;; sequence states and allow live interaction with it.
;;; I try to think of it as a more alive version of an agnostic driver

;;; # Here I layout my assumptions and conventions:
;;;   ## about word size and size conventions:
;;;      CPU's are for me 64 bits.
;;;      "li" or "l" stands for little so if you read linat is a
;;;      little natural number
;;;      (or what you would classically call an unint8)
;;;      mi/m => middling => 16 bits
;;;      hu/h => huge => 32 bits
;;;      gi/g => gigantormous => 64 bits.
;;;   ## registers as structures:
;;;      1. Since architectures only agree on having direct access the lower
;;;      32 bit part of a register. Then access to their subdivisions
;;;      must then be seen as actions on the registers.
;;;      2. Architectures seem to agree that there are "special" registers
;;;      so structs must capture their use cases "jobs"
;;;   ## job conventions:
;;;      0 => general purpose
;;;      1 => instruction pointer
;;;      2 => instruction holder
;;;      3 => flaging/signaling

(strdef (gireg . 'make-gireg)
  "This is the structure appended onto the register concept"
  ((ginat . id) 0)
  ((linat . job) 0)
  ((ginat . size) 0))

important note for the curious minds. I use LLMS to get high
overviews of complex topics when learning them for the first time
and to get reading suggestions. This was redacted by gemini. I'm
not a genius. I'll build My first IR here.

To capture a CPU's Instruction Set Architecture (ISA)
cleanly in your IR, you need to look past the marketing specs
(like the number of cores) and focus on the hard mathematical
and physical invariants that every modern processor forces
a compiler to respect.When you are writing your danger-board
translator to emit machine instructions, these are the fundamental
structural axioms you will have to model.

1. The Execution Lifecycle (The Von Neumann Invariant) At its
lowest layer, every CPU is an infinite, synchronous loop. It
doesn't matter if it's an x86_64 chip in a server, an ARM chip in
a phone, or a RISC-V microcontroller. They all execute a strict
state-machine sequence:

Fetch --> Decode --> Execute

The Implications for your IR:Your runtime environment must always
track a minimum of two special registers that manage this loop:

The Program Counter (PC) / Instruction Pointer (IP): A register that
holds the physical memory address of the next instruction to execute.
Every time an instruction runs, the PC advances linearly, unless a
branch instruction explicitly overwrites it.

The Instruction Register (IR): The internal slot where the current
binary opcode sits while the execution engine decodes its bits into
control signals.

2. Memory Geometry and Alignment Restrictions

While we like to think of memory as a continuous, fluid line of bytes,
hardware treats memory as a strict grid of machine words
(typically 32-bit or 64-bit blocks).

The Invariants:

Word Size: The native bit-width of the internal data pathways and
general-purpose registers (32 bits or 64 bits). This dictates the
maximum size of a pointer.

Alignment Invariants: CPUs fetch memory in whole-word chunks. If a
64-bit integer is stored at a memory address that is a multiple of 8,
the CPU fetches it in exactly one clock cycle. If it is split across a
word boundary (unaligned), the CPU must perform two memory fetches,
shift the bits, and mask them together. On some architectures
(like strict ARM or MIPS), unaligned access doesn't just slow things
down—it triggers a hardware exception that crashes the program.

3. Register Asymmetry (The Structural Roles)

You mentioned that registers process or signal stuff. Across almost
all ISAs, registers are strictly divided into three functional categories
that your compiler must manage:

General Purpose Registers (GPRs): The CPU's hyper-fast, local
scratchpad. This is where mathematical operations actually happen
(e.g., adding two numbers).

Status / Flags Register: A single register where individual bits (flags)
are flipped automatically by the ALU after an operation. The most important
invariant flags across all architectures are:

Z (Zero Flag): Set if the last result was exactly 0.

C (Carry Flag): Set if an addition overflowed the maximum bit-width.

S/N (Sign/Negative Flag): Set if the result was a negative number.Your
IR's conditional jumps (if, loop) will ultimately translate into machine
instructions that look at these exact flags.

The Stack Pointer (SP): A dedicated register holding the memory address of
the current top of the call stack.

4. The Stack and Calling Conventions

A CPU has absolutely no native concept of a "function," a "scope,"
or "local variables." It only knows how to jump to an address.
To support functions, every single modern architecture relies on a
Stack Invariant.

The Invariant:

Memory is partitioned so that a chunk of it acts as a Last-In,
First-Out (LIFO) stack that grows downward (usually) from high memory
addresses to low memory addresses.When a function is called, the CPU
pushes the current Program Counter onto the stack (the Return Address)
and jumps to the function.

When the function finishes, a ret instruction pops that address back
off the stack and into the PC.
Your compiler’s execution engine will have to respect the target ISA's
Calling Convention—the strict public protocol defining which registers
are allowed to hold function arguments, which registers must be
preserved before jumping, and how the stack frame must be cleaned up.

5. The Memory Hierarchy & The Myth of Uniform Speed

From the perspective of your language's semantics, memory access takes
uniform time. From the perspective of the hardware, distance is destiny.
The Invariants:

Registers: 0 clock cycles (instantaneous).

L1/L2/L3 Caches: Tiny, incredibly expensive pools of static RAM built
directly into the processor die (1 to 20 clock cycles).

Main RAM: External Dynamic RAM
(potentially hundreds of clock cycles of latency).When a CPU requests
data from RAM, it never fetches just the byte you asked for. It
fetches an entire Cache Line (usually 64 continuous bytes) and stores
it in the L1 cache. If your IR structures data lineally in memory
(Data-Oriented Design), the CPU hits the cache every time. If your IR
jumps around chasing pointers randomly, the CPU spends 99% of its time
sitting completely idle, waiting for the RAM wires to charge.

How to Blend This into Your Blurry Compiler

Because your IR is written as first-class S-expressions, you don't
have to build a complex abstract model for these constraints.
You can represent the target CPU's invariants directly as an
explicit environment profile.
When your code enters a danger-board targeted at an x86_64 profile,
your compiler macros will know:

Arguments must be bound to the RDI, RSI, and RDX registers
(the x86_64 calling convention).

Any structure you allocate must have its memory layout padded to
8-byte boundaries (Alignment Invariant).Conditionals must be lowered
into code that reads the status flag register.

By treating these hardware axioms as strict rules within your
functional environment, your IR can seamlessly transform from
high-level mathematical expressions into beautiful,
hardware-aware execution streams.